WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
The topic of today's lecture is the control and assessment of the effectiveness of marketing activity.

00:11.000 --> 00:13.000
This lecture consists of three sections.

00:14.000 --> 00:19.000
In the first section, we will consider the problem of measuring the effectiveness of marketing as such.

00:20.000 --> 00:25.000
We will look at the main model, which is at the heart of the entire assessment of the effectiveness of marketing.

00:26.000 --> 00:29.000
This model is called the chain model of effectiveness.

00:30.000 --> 00:34.000
In the second section, we will consider the main marketing metrics.

00:35.000 --> 00:40.000
This is a tool for measuring the various aspects of the marketing activity of a company,

00:41.000 --> 00:44.000
which is later used for control.

00:45.000 --> 00:48.000
We will consider the control of marketing activity in the third section.

00:49.000 --> 00:54.000
Now let's see what are the goals and tasks of our lecture today.

00:54.000 --> 01:00.000
First of all, in order to start studying the control and assessment of marketing activity,

01:01.000 --> 01:04.000
it is necessary to understand why this control is needed.

01:05.000 --> 01:09.000
Because many companies believe that there is no need for this.

01:10.000 --> 01:15.000
We will provide arguments in favor of the fact that control is necessary for every company.

01:16.000 --> 01:20.000
And every company must study the results of its investment in marketing

01:21.000 --> 01:23.000
and control them on a regular basis.

01:24.000 --> 01:27.000
Then we will study the main marketing metrics.

01:28.000 --> 01:31.000
I have completed quite a lot of practical tasks.

01:32.000 --> 01:34.000
And by the end of the second section,

01:35.000 --> 01:40.000
you all should learn to calculate the main quantitative indicators in marketing on your own,

01:41.000 --> 01:45.000
to use them in your companies to measure the effectiveness of marketing activity.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.000
After that, we will consider the main principles of marketing control.

01:50.000 --> 01:53.000
We will see how the marketing metrics we have studied

01:54.000 --> 01:58.000
are used for complex control of the marketing activity of companies

01:59.000 --> 02:01.000
and assessment of the results of the activity.

02:07.000 --> 02:11.000
We will proceed to the first part, to the execution of our first task,

02:12.000 --> 02:17.000
to show that the control and assessment of the effectiveness of marketing activity are really necessary for companies.

02:17.000 --> 02:23.000
Many companies in practice believe that such an activity as control is not necessary.

02:24.000 --> 02:26.000
It is just a waste of money,

02:27.000 --> 02:31.000
the time of employees and no tangible effect this activity gives.

02:32.000 --> 02:35.000
Many companies really neglect control.

02:36.000 --> 02:39.000
And, it would seem, they live quite happily.

02:40.000 --> 02:43.000
But this is just the situation that is said to be happiness in ignorance.

02:44.000 --> 02:48.000
Recently, a study was conducted by several American companies,

02:49.000 --> 02:53.000
as a result of which they found that for every dollar invested in marketing,

02:54.000 --> 02:56.000
they get a profit of only 70 cents.

02:57.000 --> 03:01.000
They were horrified to find that all those huge investments in marketing that they made

03:02.000 --> 03:04.000
actually brought losses to companies.

03:05.000 --> 03:07.000
They could live in ignorance and on,

03:08.000 --> 03:11.000
but now they understand that their marketing activity is ineffective

03:11.000 --> 03:14.000
and they should correct their actions.

03:15.000 --> 03:19.000
And think about whether your marketing is actually effective or not.

03:20.000 --> 03:24.000
Do you get a profit from those investments that you invest in advertising

03:25.000 --> 03:29.000
or other aspects of promoting your product or in the development of new products?

03:30.000 --> 03:33.000
Therefore, every company must use control

03:34.000 --> 03:37.000
of the results of its marketing activity on a regular basis

03:37.000 --> 03:41.000
and find out the problems that arise in due time.

03:42.000 --> 03:46.000
The problem of neglect of the control of the marketing activity

03:47.000 --> 03:50.000
is typical for both foreign and Russian companies.

03:51.000 --> 03:54.000
Among the foreign managers, a survey was conducted, which gave the following results.

03:55.000 --> 03:59.000
66% of managers said that the control of the assessment of the effectiveness of marketing

04:00.000 --> 04:02.000
is the most relevant problem for them today.

04:02.000 --> 04:06.000
The problem is not only that the marketing budgets of many companies

04:07.000 --> 04:12.000
are millions of dollars and they are second in many cases after the production costs.

04:13.000 --> 04:17.000
The problem is that, unfortunately, many marketing specialists

04:18.000 --> 04:21.000
still do not have the qualifications to fully assess the effectiveness of marketing.

04:22.000 --> 04:24.000
As for Russian companies,

04:25.000 --> 04:28.000
many directors of Russian enterprises often say

04:28.000 --> 04:33.000
that Russian marketers often neglect the control of the effectiveness of their marketing activities

04:34.000 --> 04:40.000
and cannot assess whether the marketing decisions they make are reasonable.

04:41.000 --> 04:45.000
At a recent conference on the problems of teaching marketing in Russia,

04:46.000 --> 04:49.000
the director of the marketing company Fort Motor Company stated

04:50.000 --> 04:54.000
that her company also has a problem of assessing the effectiveness of marketing.

04:54.000 --> 04:56.000
It is related to the following.

04:57.000 --> 05:00.000
Russian marketers can develop the most creative advertising campaigns,

05:01.000 --> 05:04.000
can offer great ideas, but they do not think about

05:05.000 --> 05:09.000
whether it is reasonable to implement these ideas in terms of profit for the company.

05:10.000 --> 05:12.000
They just do not know how to assess the effectiveness of marketing decisions.

05:13.000 --> 05:17.000
This is a really relevant problem for both Russia and foreign companies.

05:17.000 --> 05:25.000
If we recall the marketing mix and the 4P or 5-7P that we considered in the general marketing module,

05:26.000 --> 05:27.000
we need to add the following.

05:28.000 --> 05:31.000
The most important P in marketing is profitability.

05:32.000 --> 05:35.000
And every company should understand that marketing is not the goal itself,

05:36.000 --> 05:40.000
it is a tool for increasing the company's profits and improving the results of its activities.

05:40.000 --> 05:51.000
Now, after we are sure that the control of marketing activities is really necessary for any company,

05:52.000 --> 05:56.000
we will move on to the first section of our lectures

05:57.000 --> 06:01.000
and consider what place control takes in terms of marketing.

06:02.000 --> 06:03.000
Pay attention to the slide.

06:03.000 --> 06:09.000
You see that any marketing plan starts with control and ends with control.

06:10.000 --> 06:15.000
At the beginning, the company sets a summary of the control indicators of its activity,

06:16.000 --> 06:20.000
which it will use at the end of the marketing plan to implement control.

06:21.000 --> 06:24.000
Have the goals that were set by the company at the beginning been achieved?

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
Do the real results correspond to the desired results?

06:28.000 --> 06:33.000
Thus, control is an integral part of the marketing activity of any company.

06:34.000 --> 06:37.000
Let's consider the model of the chain of marketing effectiveness.

06:38.000 --> 06:39.000
The essence of this model is as follows.

06:40.000 --> 06:43.000
Each company has its own strategy.

06:44.000 --> 06:47.000
There is a set of functional strategies that you have already studied.

06:48.000 --> 06:53.000
But the implementation of any strategy involves certain tactical actions of the company.

06:53.000 --> 06:59.000
In the slide, you can see how the strategy block is being used to implement the tactical actions of the company.

07:00.000 --> 07:04.000
It is easy to assume that any tactical actions,

07:05.000 --> 07:08.000
be it the implementation of an advertising campaign or the development of a new product,

07:09.000 --> 07:11.000
involve certain costs.

07:12.000 --> 07:15.000
By investing money in these tactical actions,

07:16.000 --> 07:20.000
the company assumes that it will get a significant result.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
Namely, the increase in profits, for example,

07:24.000 --> 07:26.000
or the change in other indicators of the company's activity.

07:27.000 --> 07:29.000
What actions can take place?

07:30.000 --> 07:37.000
In the slide, you can see that tactical actions can affect the internal and external environment of the company in a certain way.

07:38.000 --> 07:41.000
First, they influence the buyers.

07:42.000 --> 07:46.000
For example, they change their attitude to the product or change the behavior of the buyer.

07:47.000 --> 07:51.000
Secondly, these actions influence the market.

07:52.000 --> 07:56.000
Thirdly, they influence the financial indicators of the company's activity.

07:57.000 --> 08:00.000
For example, the level of profit the company receives.

08:01.000 --> 08:05.000
When the company invests money in certain tactical actions,

08:06.000 --> 08:09.000
the company assumes that it will get certain results.

08:10.000 --> 08:12.000
The results can be as follows.

08:12.000 --> 08:16.000
In the right part of the slide, you can see a list of possible results.

08:17.000 --> 08:21.000
On the one hand, they can reflect the change in the company's position in the market.

08:22.000 --> 08:24.000
For example, the share of the company's market can increase.

08:25.000 --> 08:29.000
Secondly, these actions can increase the company's market capital

08:30.000 --> 08:33.000
and increase the value of the company's relationship with the consumers.

08:34.000 --> 08:38.000
And finally, the company's profit or share price can change.

08:39.000 --> 08:45.000
Here we can see that on one side of the scale there are the company's costs for the tactical actions,

08:46.000 --> 08:48.000
the conditioned strategies,

08:49.000 --> 08:55.000
and on the other side there is the result expressed in the aspects related to the finances,

08:56.000 --> 08:58.000
the market and the consumers.

08:59.000 --> 09:03.000
If we compare what we have invested and what we have received,

09:03.000 --> 09:09.000
we can evaluate how effective our marketing activity is.

09:10.000 --> 09:13.000
Any company has an idea of the size of its marketing budget.

09:14.000 --> 09:22.000
But how can we evaluate the results related to the consumers, the market and the financial indicators?

09:23.000 --> 09:31.000
In order to quantify the aspects related to the consumers, the market and the financial indicators of the company's activities,

09:31.000 --> 09:34.000
there are so-called marketing metrics.

09:35.000 --> 09:37.000
What are marketing metrics?

09:38.000 --> 09:42.000
Metrics are a system of quantitative indicators that can be used in any discipline.

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
Marketing also has its own set of metrics.

09:47.000 --> 09:52.000
It is the marketing metrics that allow us to quantify the aspects related to the consumers,

09:53.000 --> 09:56.000
the market and the financial indicators of the company's activities.

09:56.000 --> 10:01.000
If we could not quantify the results of our marketing activities,

10:02.000 --> 10:05.000
we would not be able to draw a conclusion about the effectiveness of our marketing.

10:06.000 --> 10:07.000
Pay attention to the slide.

10:08.000 --> 10:11.000
Here you can see the classification of marketing metrics.

10:12.000 --> 10:17.000
All marketing metrics can be divided into several groups.

10:18.000 --> 10:21.000
In the center you can see the most important marketing metrics,

10:22.000 --> 10:25.000
those related to the market and our consumers.

10:26.000 --> 10:30.000
In addition, each marketing activity has its own metrics.

10:31.000 --> 10:33.000
Sales management has its own metrics.

10:34.000 --> 10:37.000
Advertising management also has its own marketing metrics.

10:38.000 --> 10:44.000
Today we will look at all these quantitative indicators in order to learn how to calculate them.

10:45.000 --> 10:48.000
Let's start with the metrics related to the market.

10:49.000 --> 10:55.000
The first and probably the most frequently used metric, which is known to almost everyone, is the market share.

10:56.000 --> 11:00.000
It would seem that it is not difficult to measure the share of the company's market.

11:01.000 --> 11:04.000
You just need to evaluate the volume of our product sales

11:05.000 --> 11:09.000
by the volume of our product sales plus the volume of the competitors' products.

11:10.000 --> 11:11.000
But there are some tricky things.

11:12.000 --> 11:17.000
First, we need to understand what we mean by the market in this case.

11:18.000 --> 11:22.000
Where are the boundaries of the total volume of product sales?

11:22.000 --> 11:28.000
What do we mean by the products and who should we consider as competitors?

11:29.000 --> 11:32.000
How to correctly define the boundaries of the market?

11:33.000 --> 11:34.000
Pay attention to the slide.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.000
Here is an example of a certain market.

11:39.000 --> 11:40.000
The key words are as follows.

11:41.000 --> 11:42.000
The market is a sports shoe.

11:43.000 --> 11:46.000
We are talking about the product we are considering.

11:47.000 --> 11:51.000
We are not just considering the whole shoe, but the sports shoe.

11:52.000 --> 11:54.000
The shoes for children from 2 to 16 years old.

11:55.000 --> 11:58.000
We limit our market to children's shoes.

11:59.000 --> 12:03.000
The next important aspect is the shoes for middle and high income buyers.

12:04.000 --> 12:07.000
Again, we define the boundaries of our market

12:08.000 --> 12:11.000
to better define who are our competitors.

12:12.000 --> 12:14.000
The next factor is geographical.

12:15.000 --> 12:18.000
We define the region of interest to the market.

12:19.000 --> 12:23.000
It is impossible to define the market share by defining the region.

12:24.000 --> 12:26.000
Having defined the boundaries of the market,

12:27.000 --> 12:30.000
we need to decide how to measure the market share.

12:31.000 --> 12:35.000
We can measure the market share from the point of view of the volume of sales in the monetary expression.

12:36.000 --> 12:41.000
We can also measure the market share from the point of view of the volume of sales in the natural expression,

12:42.000 --> 12:43.000
that is, in the units of the product.

12:44.000 --> 12:45.000
Which option to choose?

12:46.000 --> 12:47.000
What is better?

12:48.000 --> 12:51.000
Is it better to evaluate the market share in terms of the monetary units

12:52.000 --> 12:54.000
than in the natural expression or vice versa?

12:55.000 --> 12:57.000
In different situations, we need different assessments.

12:58.000 --> 13:00.000
What are the advantages and disadvantages?

13:01.000 --> 13:02.000
Let's consider.

13:03.000 --> 13:06.000
If we consider the market share, taking into account the volume of sales in the monetary expression,

13:07.000 --> 13:11.000
then the change in the market share can be caused by, for example,

13:12.000 --> 13:14.000
such a factor as the change in the price of the product.

13:14.000 --> 13:20.000
Here we cannot understand how the number of transactions with our products or with the products of competitors has changed.

13:21.000 --> 13:24.000
Using the market share calculated from the volume of sales in the natural expression,

13:25.000 --> 13:32.000
we can clearly understand that here we have taken into account only specific transactions and specific purchased goods.

13:33.000 --> 13:37.000
Here, the price increase or, on the contrary, the price decrease does not play any role.

13:38.000 --> 13:39.000
Now the next metric.

13:40.000 --> 13:41.000
The relative market share.

13:41.000 --> 13:45.000
What is the difference between the relative market share and the relative market share?

13:46.000 --> 13:48.000
When we consider the relative market share,

13:49.000 --> 13:52.000
we consider the volume of sales of not all the goods on our market,

13:53.000 --> 13:57.000
but only the volume of sales of our main competitor, if there is such a thing.

13:58.000 --> 14:00.000
Knowing the relative market share, we can understand

14:01.000 --> 14:04.000
how effective our activity is compared to the activity of our competitor.

14:05.000 --> 14:08.000
Accordingly, if the relative market share is more than 100%,

14:08.000 --> 14:14.000
it means that our volume of sales exceeds the volume of sales of the competitor.

14:15.000 --> 14:20.000
If it is less than 100%, then we lag behind and it is necessary to take any action.

14:21.000 --> 14:22.000
Pay attention to the next slide.

14:23.000 --> 14:28.000
Here you see the matrix of the Boston Consulting Group.

14:29.000 --> 14:34.000
Here all the goods of the company are divided into some categories.

14:34.000 --> 14:40.000
As you can see, they are divided according to the criteria of the market potential and the relative market share.

14:41.000 --> 14:44.000
These are the indicators that we have just considered.

14:45.000 --> 14:49.000
The next metric that needs to be studied is the market concentration index.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.000
Different markets have different concentrations.

14:54.000 --> 14:56.000
In some markets there are many small players,

14:57.000 --> 14:59.000
in other markets there are large companies.

14:59.000 --> 15:05.000
For each company it is necessary to understand the market it operates in,

15:06.000 --> 15:07.000
what is the concentration on it.

15:08.000 --> 15:10.000
To calculate the concentration index,

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
we need to add up the market share of several players.

15:16.000 --> 15:17.000
Usually, it is 3 or 4 companies.

15:18.000 --> 15:21.000
These are companies with the largest market share.

15:30.000 --> 15:33.000
Now let's discuss the answer.

15:34.000 --> 15:38.000
In our task, the concentration index of the market is 55%.

15:39.000 --> 15:41.000
This is not a very high indicator, but not very low.

15:42.000 --> 15:45.000
This means that there are several fairly serious players in the market,

15:46.000 --> 15:48.000
and the company must take this into account in its activities.

15:49.000 --> 15:54.000
The next metric related to the market is the brand development index.

15:55.000 --> 15:57.000
How do we calculate the brand development index?

15:57.000 --> 16:02.000
We take the sales volume of our brand to the consumers of a certain group.

16:03.000 --> 16:08.000
For example, we choose a group of consumers, state institutions,

16:09.000 --> 16:14.000
and calculate the brand development index in this category of consumers, in this segment.

16:15.000 --> 16:20.000
To do this, we divide the sales volume of our goods to this group of buyers

16:21.000 --> 16:24.000
into the total sales volume of our brand.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
What does the brand development index tell us about a certain segment of buyers?

16:29.000 --> 16:33.000
By comparing the brand development index in different segments of buyers,

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
we can understand which of these segments is stronger or weaker.

16:39.000 --> 16:40.000
What does it mean?

16:41.000 --> 16:45.000
Which segment consumes our goods or services to a greater extent, and which to a lesser extent?

16:55.000 --> 16:59.000
The correct answer to this problem is the brand development index

17:00.000 --> 17:04.000
in the state institution segment is 1.32.

17:05.000 --> 17:06.000
What does this mean?

17:07.000 --> 17:14.000
If we assume that the average segment among all the segments of our consumers

17:15.000 --> 17:17.000
has a development index of 1,

17:18.000 --> 17:24.000
then this segment of the state institution consumes our goods more actively.

17:25.000 --> 17:27.000
This is one of the main segments.

17:28.000 --> 17:34.000
If a company has a segment of consumers with the highest brand development index,

17:35.000 --> 17:38.000
it means that these are the main consumers of the company,

17:39.000 --> 17:41.000
and they should be given maximum attention.

17:42.000 --> 17:47.000
In some cases, knowing the brand development index in different segments,

17:48.000 --> 17:49.000
companies become niche.

17:50.000 --> 17:54.000
They switch all their efforts to this particular segment and work only with this segment.

17:55.000 --> 17:57.000
All other segments are secondary for them.

17:58.000 --> 18:00.000
This is one of the possible strategies of a company.

18:01.000 --> 18:03.000
The next metric is related to the market.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.000
It is the coefficient of the brand penetration into the market.

18:07.000 --> 18:09.000
This metric is calculated as follows.

18:09.000 --> 18:13.000
We take the number of buyers who buy our goods

18:14.000 --> 18:17.000
and divide it by the total number of potential buyers in the market.

18:18.000 --> 18:23.000
Thus, we can understand how actively our goods are used.

18:34.000 --> 18:36.000
The correct answer to this problem is

18:36.000 --> 18:41.000
that the coefficient of the brand penetration into the market is 2.5%.

18:42.000 --> 18:43.000
This is a small number.

18:44.000 --> 18:49.000
It means that only 2.5% of potential buyers buy our goods.

18:50.000 --> 18:57.000
In this case, a company should either increase the awareness of its buyers,

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
or change their attitude to our goods,

19:01.000 --> 19:03.000
that is, to cover more and more buyers.

19:03.000 --> 19:08.000
There are cases when the coefficient of the brand penetration into the market is very high,

19:09.000 --> 19:10.000
and it is close to 100%.

19:11.000 --> 19:14.000
What should a company do in this situation to increase the volume of sales?

19:15.000 --> 19:18.000
In this case, there is no one else to attract.

19:19.000 --> 19:22.000
All buyers or almost everyone buys our goods.

19:23.000 --> 19:25.000
In this case, a company should choose another strategy.

19:26.000 --> 19:29.000
It is possible to encourage buyers to buy our goods more often

19:30.000 --> 19:32.000
or to buy our goods in a larger volume.

19:33.000 --> 19:39.000
Thus, we see that a company needs to know the coefficient of the brand penetration into the market

19:40.000 --> 19:41.000
or a certain product into the market

19:42.000 --> 19:46.000
to understand what actions to take to improve the performance of its activities.

19:47.000 --> 19:53.000
The next metric related to the market is called a share of the wallet.

19:54.000 --> 19:55.000
What does it mean?

19:56.000 --> 20:01.000
Imagine a buyer who goes to the store every day and buys goods of a certain category.

20:01.000 --> 20:03.000
Let's choose a certain product category.

20:04.000 --> 20:05.000
Let's say it's dairy products.

20:06.000 --> 20:09.000
Our buyer buys dairy products of various brands.

20:10.000 --> 20:17.000
If we take all the total costs of the buyer for dairy products in the denominator,

20:18.000 --> 20:22.000
and there will be costs for dairy products of our brand,

20:22.000 --> 20:34.000
we will calculate the cost of all the brands of this buyer.

20:45.000 --> 20:50.000
If the share of the wallet is high, the buyer buys goods of our brand only.

20:50.000 --> 20:53.000
Maybe he rarely buys goods of other brands.

20:54.000 --> 20:56.000
I mean goods of a certain category.

20:57.000 --> 20:59.000
In this case, what can we do?

21:00.000 --> 21:04.000
We can only encourage him to buy goods in a larger volume.

21:05.000 --> 21:07.000
We have no reason to lure this buyer to competitors,

21:08.000 --> 21:10.000
because he does not buy goods of competitors.

21:11.000 --> 21:13.000
If the share of the wallet is not high,

21:14.000 --> 21:17.000
it means that the buyer buys both our goods of this category

21:17.000 --> 21:19.000
and goods of competitors.

21:20.000 --> 21:24.000
In this case, our primary task is to switch the buyer

21:25.000 --> 21:29.000
from buying goods of competitors to buying goods of our brand.

21:30.000 --> 21:34.000
We see that depending on the value of the share of the wallet,

21:35.000 --> 21:38.000
we can take various actions to improve the performance of our activity.

21:39.000 --> 21:42.000
Now, having considered the main metrics related to the market,

21:43.000 --> 21:45.000
we move on to metrics related to consumers.

21:45.000 --> 21:49.000
On the slide, you can see the so-called hierarchy of effects.

21:50.000 --> 21:54.000
The chain of awareness, attitude, behavior.

21:55.000 --> 22:00.000
This is a chain that the buyer needs to go through to make a purchase.

22:01.000 --> 22:03.000
Why do we need to consider this chain?

22:04.000 --> 22:06.000
It would seem that if we are interested in a deal,

22:07.000 --> 22:08.000
if we are interested in buying goods,

22:09.000 --> 22:11.000
why do we need to consider awareness and attitude?

22:12.000 --> 22:14.000
There are very serious arguments here.

22:15.000 --> 22:19.000
If a situation arises when the volume of sales is not high or not high enough,

22:20.000 --> 22:22.000
because any company's sales volume is not always high enough,

22:23.000 --> 22:24.000
and you always want more,

22:25.000 --> 22:30.000
then you need to understand the reason why the buyer refuses to buy our goods.

22:31.000 --> 22:32.000
The reasons can be different.

22:33.000 --> 22:38.000
These reasons can be identified by analyzing the behavior of the buyer at different stages.

22:39.000 --> 22:42.000
Let's say, the buyer may not buy our goods,

22:42.000 --> 22:46.000
because he does not know about the existence of our brand.

22:47.000 --> 22:49.000
That is, awareness of our product is low.

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
Here we need to take certain actions,

22:53.000 --> 22:55.000
for example, increase our advertising budget.

22:56.000 --> 22:59.000
There are situations when the buyer refuses to buy for other reasons.

23:00.000 --> 23:01.000
When the awareness is high,

23:02.000 --> 23:05.000
but the attitude of the buyer to the product is not good enough,

23:06.000 --> 23:08.000
and therefore the buyer refuses to buy.

23:09.000 --> 23:11.000
Knowing that the problem is in the attitude,

23:12.000 --> 23:14.000
we will adopt completely different strategies

23:15.000 --> 23:17.000
than in the case when we know that the problem is in awareness.

23:18.000 --> 23:22.000
If we talk about measuring awareness,

23:23.000 --> 23:25.000
we need to understand that this is a metric,

23:26.000 --> 23:29.000
which means that we measure awareness quantitatively.

23:30.000 --> 23:32.000
How to measure awareness quantitatively?

23:33.000 --> 23:36.000
First of all, you need to identify several types of awareness.

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
Spontaneous awareness means that

23:39.000 --> 23:43.000
when the question is asked about the goods of a certain category,

23:44.000 --> 23:48.000
the buyer without a hint calls our brand or the name of our company.

23:49.000 --> 23:51.000
And the next type of awareness is allocated,

23:52.000 --> 23:54.000
the so-called Top of Mind indicator.

23:55.000 --> 23:56.000
What does it mean?

23:57.000 --> 24:00.000
This indicator can be translated as the first in the list,

24:01.000 --> 24:02.000
or what comes to mind first.

24:03.000 --> 24:05.000
Here the survey is conducted as follows.

24:06.000 --> 24:07.000
When the question is asked,

24:08.000 --> 24:11.000
what brands of goods of a certain category do you know?

24:12.000 --> 24:15.000
And the brand that he calls first,

24:16.000 --> 24:18.000
or the brand that he calls first,

24:19.000 --> 24:20.000
is called Top of Mind.

24:21.000 --> 24:23.000
This indicator reflects the percentage of buyers

24:24.000 --> 24:27.000
who named our brand or the name of our company

24:28.000 --> 24:32.000
as the first in the list of brands or goods of a certain category.

24:33.000 --> 24:35.000
How to measure the quantitatively?

24:36.000 --> 24:41.000
This is the percentage of buyers who named our brand or the name of our company

24:42.000 --> 24:44.000
without a hint.

24:45.000 --> 24:46.000
Not necessarily the first in the list.

24:47.000 --> 24:50.000
And how to measure the quantitatively?

24:51.000 --> 24:56.000
In this case, when the buyer receives a list of companies

24:57.000 --> 25:00.000
and marks the brands that he knows,

25:00.000 --> 25:05.000
we record the percentage of buyers who know our product

25:06.000 --> 25:10.000
based on the list they have.

25:11.000 --> 25:12.000
Next.

25:13.000 --> 25:15.000
The most difficult thing is to measure the quantitatively.

25:16.000 --> 25:17.000
It would seem paradoxical.

25:18.000 --> 25:19.000
How to measure the quantitatively?

25:20.000 --> 25:23.000
Here, the marketers have found a solution.

25:24.000 --> 25:26.000
Of course, the quantitatively is measured

25:26.000 --> 25:30.000
by conducting a marketing survey of the buyers.

25:31.000 --> 25:35.000
To measure the quantitatively, it is not enough to measure it in general.

25:36.000 --> 25:40.000
Because there is no clear understanding of what the quantitatively is.

25:41.000 --> 25:43.000
One buyer will say that he has a good relationship,

25:44.000 --> 25:45.000
another will say that it is not good enough.

25:46.000 --> 25:47.000
But this information will not give us anything.

25:48.000 --> 25:50.000
We will not be able to understand the essence of the relationship

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
between our buyer and our brand or our product.

25:53.000 --> 25:57.000
Therefore, the marketers have divided the concept of the relationship

25:58.000 --> 25:59.000
into several characteristics.

26:00.000 --> 26:01.000
The first is the image.

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
How to measure the quantitatively?

26:06.000 --> 26:10.000
In the survey, the buyers are offered to evaluate a number of statements on a scale.

26:11.000 --> 26:14.000
Usually, this scale is 5 or 7.

26:15.000 --> 26:19.000
1 means that the buyer does not agree with the statement at all.

26:20.000 --> 26:24.000
5 or 7 means that the buyer absolutely agrees with the statement.

26:25.000 --> 26:27.000
What statements can be given about the image?

26:28.000 --> 26:30.000
For example, the statement is given.

26:31.000 --> 26:36.000
I believe that the image of this brand corresponds to my way of life.

26:37.000 --> 26:41.000
Or, for example, I believe that the image of this brand suggests

26:42.000 --> 26:46.000
that these products are purchased by people of mature age.

26:46.000 --> 26:49.000
And the buyer evaluates whether he agrees with this or not.

26:50.000 --> 26:54.000
And having quantitative assessments of the agreement or disagreement

26:55.000 --> 26:57.000
with this statement of potential buyers,

26:58.000 --> 27:02.000
we can draw a conclusion about what, in the opinion of consumers,

27:03.000 --> 27:04.000
the image of our product is.

27:05.000 --> 27:09.000
The next aspect of the relationship is the price-quality ratio.

27:10.000 --> 27:13.000
Companies and consumers may have completely different opinions

27:13.000 --> 27:15.000
about the price-quality ratio.

27:16.000 --> 27:19.000
Almost all companies believe that they have adequate prices

27:20.000 --> 27:21.000
and very high quality.

27:22.000 --> 27:25.000
But the buyers may disagree with this for various reasons.

27:26.000 --> 27:28.000
Because they do not know enough about the quality of the goods.

27:29.000 --> 27:30.000
Because they have a biased opinion.

27:31.000 --> 27:33.000
Or, in general, the attitude to the product does not allow them

27:34.000 --> 27:36.000
to say that the product has high quality.

27:37.000 --> 27:41.000
That is, some external factors affect their opinion.

27:42.000 --> 27:46.000
Nevertheless, we need to evaluate how the buyers perceive

27:47.000 --> 27:48.000
the price-quality ratio.

27:49.000 --> 27:50.000
And this perception is always subjective.

27:51.000 --> 27:52.000
How to do this?

27:53.000 --> 27:54.000
How to get quantitative assessments?

27:55.000 --> 27:57.000
In this case, again, there are surveys of potential buyers.

27:58.000 --> 28:01.000
They are offered the same 5 or 7-point scale

28:02.000 --> 28:04.000
from completely disagreeable to completely agreeable.

28:05.000 --> 28:07.000
But here such statements are offered.

28:08.000 --> 28:11.000
One of the most common statements used in this case

28:12.000 --> 28:16.000
is that the goods of a given brand have an adequate price-quality ratio.

28:17.000 --> 28:21.000
And here our buyer will either agree with this or disagree.

28:22.000 --> 28:27.000
Another option is to say that the goods of a given brand

28:28.000 --> 28:32.000
have a higher quality than the corresponding price.

28:32.000 --> 28:39.000
The next aspect of the quantitative attitude is the perceived quality.

28:40.000 --> 28:45.000
Here, too, the buyer is offered a scale from completely low quality

28:46.000 --> 28:47.000
to extremely high quality.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
And we get quantitative assessments of the perceived quality of our product.

28:52.000 --> 28:55.000
Many companies are surprised when they find out

28:56.000 --> 28:57.000
that the perceived quality of their goods or services

28:57.000 --> 29:02.000
is significantly different from the perceived quality of their products.

29:03.000 --> 29:06.000
Often, the buyer does not have enough information about the quality.

29:07.000 --> 29:10.000
Therefore, it is important to measure the perceived quality,

29:11.000 --> 29:13.000
not the real one, whatever it is.

29:14.000 --> 29:16.000
The next indicator that is measured

29:17.000 --> 29:20.000
during the study of the buyer's attitude to goods or brands

29:21.000 --> 29:22.000
is the intention.

29:23.000 --> 29:25.000
Here, the most various intentions are studied,

29:25.000 --> 29:28.000
that is, the characteristics of the behavior of the buyer.

29:29.000 --> 29:33.000
And also, a scale is used from completely disagreeable to completely agreeable

29:34.000 --> 29:36.000
to assess various statements.

29:37.000 --> 29:39.000
Here, the statements are associated with the actions

29:40.000 --> 29:44.000
that the buyer intends or does not intend to make.

29:45.000 --> 29:47.000
These can be completely different statements.

29:48.000 --> 29:52.000
For example, I plan to refuse to purchase a product of your brand.

29:52.000 --> 29:55.000
Here, the buyer assesses whether he agrees with this statement,

29:56.000 --> 29:59.000
that he plans to refuse or does not agree, that he does not plan to.

30:00.000 --> 30:02.000
There can be more complex statements.

30:03.000 --> 30:07.000
For example, if I find that there is no product available in the store

30:08.000 --> 30:10.000
of the research brand,

30:11.000 --> 30:13.000
then I will not purchase a product of the competing brand.

30:14.000 --> 30:17.000
Accordingly, the buyer notes whether he agrees with this statement or not.

30:17.000 --> 30:21.000
Here, the most various intentions of the buyer can be studied,

30:22.000 --> 30:24.000
depending on what interests us at the moment,

30:25.000 --> 30:28.000
or what aspects of our activity are relevant at the moment.

30:29.000 --> 30:30.000
And the last aspect,

30:31.000 --> 30:33.000
related to the buyer's attitude to goods,

30:34.000 --> 30:35.000
is the intention to buy.

30:36.000 --> 30:37.000
Here, a simple scale is used,

30:38.000 --> 30:43.000
from absolutely agreeable to completely agreeable.

30:44.000 --> 30:46.000
And, accordingly, the intermediate values.

30:47.000 --> 30:49.000
Here, we can find out what percentage of buyers

30:50.000 --> 30:52.000
may or may not buy our product.

30:53.000 --> 30:55.000
Then we will talk about the intention to buy,

30:56.000 --> 30:59.000
and see how this metric can be used to assess the potential volume of sales.

31:00.000 --> 31:02.000
The next metric, related to the consumer,

31:03.000 --> 31:05.000
is the consumer satisfaction.

31:06.000 --> 31:09.000
The consumer satisfaction can also be estimated quantitatively.

31:10.000 --> 31:11.000
In the slide, you can see an example

31:12.000 --> 31:16.000
of how the consumer satisfaction was estimated quantitatively during the study.

31:17.000 --> 31:19.000
What conclusions can we draw from this assessment?

31:20.000 --> 31:24.000
Here, you can see that 50% of consumers are satisfied with goods or services

31:25.000 --> 31:27.000
studied in this case.

31:28.000 --> 31:31.000
But we see that the extremely satisfied buyers are twice as few.

31:32.000 --> 31:35.000
Well, and extremely unsatisfied are very few.

31:36.000 --> 31:38.000
Accordingly, knowing the ratio of the group of buyers

31:39.000 --> 31:41.000
with high satisfaction or low,

31:42.000 --> 31:44.000
we can draw the appropriate conclusions about our further actions.

31:44.000 --> 31:48.000
It rarely happens, or rather, it never happens,

31:49.000 --> 31:52.000
that all buyers are extremely satisfied with goods or services.

31:53.000 --> 31:55.000
But the satisfaction of the buyer can be managed.

31:56.000 --> 31:57.000
How?

31:58.000 --> 32:00.000
First of all, by managing expectations.

32:01.000 --> 32:04.000
If a company creates high expectations about its goods or services,

32:05.000 --> 32:11.000
then the buyers are not very pleased with their real performance of goods or services.

32:11.000 --> 32:15.000
It turns out that we are to blame for the reduction of satisfaction.

32:16.000 --> 32:19.000
If we do not increase the expectations of the buyers,

32:20.000 --> 32:24.000
it may turn out that the buyers will say that they are more satisfied

32:25.000 --> 32:29.000
with what they received, because they did not expect such a high level of service.

32:30.000 --> 32:34.000
For example, they did not expect that the goods would be of such high quality.

32:35.000 --> 32:40.000
The next metric used to study consumers is the desire to recommend.

32:41.000 --> 32:42.000
It is quite simple.

32:43.000 --> 32:45.000
During the survey of buyers, we determine

32:46.000 --> 32:51.000
what percentage of buyers are ready to recommend our goods to the representatives of their reference group,

32:52.000 --> 32:53.000
for example, to their friends or acquaintances.

32:54.000 --> 32:57.000
The next metric is more complex — the desire to search.

32:58.000 --> 33:03.000
It means that there are buyers who will not purchase the goods of the competitor

33:04.000 --> 33:05.000
without discovering that our goods are available.

33:06.000 --> 33:08.000
In this case, we will call them the ones who want to search.

33:08.000 --> 33:12.000
Having determined the percentage of buyers who want to search for our goods,

33:13.000 --> 33:15.000
regardless of whether they are in the store or not,

33:16.000 --> 33:17.000
and will not buy the goods of another brand,

33:18.000 --> 33:22.000
this percentage is called the desire to search.

33:23.000 --> 33:27.000
The next metric related to buyers is the coefficient of retention of consumers.

33:28.000 --> 33:29.000
This is not such a simple coefficient.

33:30.000 --> 33:35.000
To calculate it, we need to know how many consumers we were able to retain,

33:35.000 --> 33:40.000
that is, to keep them as customers among those we could lose.

33:41.000 --> 33:46.000
It is not so easy to determine how many buyers we could lose during a certain period.

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
If we use the contract system of relations,

33:50.000 --> 33:56.000
we can assume that if a contract with our company is signed with a buyer at the moment,

33:57.000 --> 33:58.000
and it does not expire in the near future,

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
that is, it expires beyond the limits of the period we are considering,

34:02.000 --> 34:07.000
we can say that this buyer is not at risk of loss.

34:08.000 --> 34:10.000
We do not consider him as the one we could lose,

34:11.000 --> 34:14.000
and do not take into account the coefficient of retention of buyers.

34:15.000 --> 34:20.000
We take into account only those who we could lose, but did not lose.

34:21.000 --> 34:24.000
The next metric is the profitability of consumers.

34:25.000 --> 34:29.000
It is not a secret that different buyers bring different levels of profit to the company.

34:29.000 --> 34:33.000
Some of them buy very little or buy only at low prices,

34:34.000 --> 34:38.000
others buy a large number of goods and buy at high prices.

34:39.000 --> 34:46.000
To know how to distribute the efforts to serve and establish a relationship with different consumers,

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
the company needs to understand the profitability of a particular buyer.

34:51.000 --> 34:54.000
In addition, we consider the so-called consumer value.

34:54.000 --> 34:59.000
The consumer value is the entire flow of money that we will receive from him

35:00.000 --> 35:03.000
during the entire period of interaction with this buyer.

35:04.000 --> 35:06.000
This period can be several decades.

35:07.000 --> 35:13.000
Therefore, if the company at some point wants to take actions that may lead to the loss of a client,

35:14.000 --> 35:22.000
for example, not to agree to a price reduction or to refuse to provide special conditions for a certain client,

35:22.000 --> 35:28.000
the company should remember that there are many years of possible profitable relationships ahead.

35:29.000 --> 35:32.000
In order not to lose this long-term focus,

35:33.000 --> 35:36.000
each company should assess the value of the relationship with each client.

35:37.000 --> 35:43.000
Finally, the next metrics related to the buyer are the cost of retention and the cost of attracting buyers.

35:44.000 --> 35:50.000
There is nothing complicated here, we just assess what costs we need to bear

35:50.000 --> 35:57.000
in order to attract one buyer and what costs are necessary to retain one buyer.

35:58.000 --> 36:03.000
It is no secret that retaining a buyer is much cheaper than attracting a new one.

36:04.000 --> 36:06.000
Sometimes the difference in these costs reaches tens of times.

36:07.000 --> 36:14.000
Nevertheless, most often companies try to attract new clients,

36:14.000 --> 36:16.000
while spending large amounts of money.

36:17.000 --> 36:21.000
They pay less attention to their old clients,

36:22.000 --> 36:25.000
and they can refuse to provide services or goods to the company,

36:26.000 --> 36:28.000
leaving the competition, and many companies do not even notice this,

36:29.000 --> 36:32.000
considering that they do not need old clients, they need to attract as many new ones as possible.

36:33.000 --> 36:39.000
In order for the company not to forget what the costs are for these two types of activities,

36:40.000 --> 36:43.000
for retention and for attraction, it is necessary to calculate them.

36:44.000 --> 36:47.000
We have discussed the main metrics related to the market and buyers.

36:48.000 --> 36:51.000
Now we will discuss the questions related to the profit.

36:52.000 --> 36:55.000
Why are we discussing this question now?

36:56.000 --> 37:00.000
The fact is that the knowledge of profit, retention and margin

37:01.000 --> 37:04.000
will help us to calculate the next, more complex marketing metrics,

37:05.000 --> 37:07.000
which we will discuss later.

37:08.000 --> 37:12.000
So, here our main concepts are margin and retention.

37:12.000 --> 37:13.000
What is the difference?

37:14.000 --> 37:19.000
Margin can be calculated in rubles or other monetary units, as well as in percents.

37:20.000 --> 37:23.000
In rubles, the margin is the difference between the price of a product,

37:24.000 --> 37:26.000
that is, the price per unit of a product, and the cost of the product.

37:27.000 --> 37:31.000
Usually, these are full costs, that is, variable costs plus constant costs.

37:32.000 --> 37:33.000
The margin can be considered in percents,

37:34.000 --> 37:38.000
as the ratio of the margin in monetary units, for example, in rubles,

37:39.000 --> 37:41.000
to the price per unit of the product.

37:42.000 --> 37:46.000
Here it is necessary to distinguish the concept of margin and retention.

37:47.000 --> 37:49.000
If we say that the margin is measured in percents,

37:50.000 --> 37:51.000
the retention is also in percents,

37:52.000 --> 37:54.000
we cannot say that it is the same thing, it is not the same thing at all.

37:55.000 --> 37:56.000
What is the difference?

37:57.000 --> 37:59.000
The margin is the percentage of the price of a product,

38:00.000 --> 38:01.000
that is, of the entire price value,

38:02.000 --> 38:04.000
and the retention is the percentage of the costs.

38:05.000 --> 38:06.000
To calculate the retention,

38:07.000 --> 38:10.000
we need to multiply the percentage of the retention by the costs.

38:10.000 --> 38:11.000
To calculate the margin,

38:12.000 --> 38:15.000
we need to multiply the percentage of the margin by the cost of the product,

38:16.000 --> 38:17.000
and this will result in different quantities.

38:19.000 --> 38:21.000
And finally, what is the retention?

38:22.000 --> 38:26.000
Retention is the difference between the price of a product and the variable costs.

38:27.000 --> 38:30.000
Knowing the retention, we can calculate the margin for the variable costs,

38:31.000 --> 38:34.000
as the ratio of the retention to the price per unit of the product.

