The cost of the new product

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:26.000
Now we move on

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:28.000
to a very important question.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:30.000
The metric is called

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:32.000
the market capital.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:34.000
The market capital is considered

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:36.000
to be the main non-material asset

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:38.000
of the company.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:40.000
Due to the market capital,

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:42.000
the company can get

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:44.000
a large amount of additional profit.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:46.000
In fact, the market capital

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.000
is the additional profit,

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:50.000
that is, it is the increase in profit

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:52.000
of the company

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:54.000
due to the ownership of a certain brand.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:56.000
If we take a situation

01:00:57.000 --> 01:00:58.000
when a company sells a certain product

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:00.000
under its own brand,

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:02.000
and take another situation

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:04.000
when a company sells a similar product,

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:06.000
but without this brand,

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:08.000
and compare the profit obtained

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:10.000
in the first and second cases,

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:12.000
we can understand

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:14.000
what part of the profit,

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:16.000
what amount

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:18.000
the company gets

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:20.000
due to the brand.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:22.000
The larger the market capital,

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:24.000
the greater the additional profit

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:26.000
the company can get

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:28.000
due to its own brand.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:30.000
Many researchers

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:32.000
proposed different algorithms

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:34.000
and methods of calculating the market capital.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:36.000
Let's take a look at several of these methods.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:38.000
The first method

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:40.000
was proposed by the advertising agency

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:42.000
Young and Rubicon.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:44.000
Here you can see

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:46.000
the four indicators

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:48.000
that measure the market capital.

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:50.000
That is, the perceived difference

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:52.000
between the brand's life,

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:54.000
brand's respect and brand's knowledge.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:56.000
If we compare

01:01:57.000 --> 01:01:58.000
our brand

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:00.000
with the brand of a competitor

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:02.000
and give certain assessments

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:04.000
regarding the brand's respect

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.000
and brand's knowledge,

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:08.000
our brand's knowledge

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:10.000
and the brand's knowledge of the competitor,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:12.000
it is better to do these measurements

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:14.000
not with the help of employees,

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:16.000
but using the opinion of consumers.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:18.000
By comparing the assessments

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.000
on these four indicators,

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:22.000
the company can understand

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:24.000
the market capital of which brand

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:26.000
is higher than our brand

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:28.000
or the brand of the competitor

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:30.000
and make the appropriate conclusions.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:32.000
The next method is similar.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:34.000
You can see that it differs

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:36.000
only by two characteristics

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:38.000
according to which the market capital is assessed.

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:40.000
The first is the attractiveness of the brand,

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:42.000
that is, the degree

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:44.000
to which the buyers want to buy the product,

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:46.000
how attractive it is for them,

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:48.000
and the trust in the brand.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:50.000
The same algorithm

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:52.000
is used by the company

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:54.000
to conduct a survey of the buyers

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:56.000
in order to determine

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:58.000
which brand

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:00.000
or brand of the competitor

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:02.000
has more market capital.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:04.000
It is impossible to say

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:06.000
that there are brands

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:08.000
that have high indicators

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:10.000
according to all these characteristics.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:12.000
This probably does not happen.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:14.000
There are some trends.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:16.000
Research shows that

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:18.000
brands that have existed for a long time

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:20.000
receive higher grades

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:22.000
in terms of uniqueness

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:24.000
and relevance in the lifestyle of the buyers.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:26.000
More modern new brands

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:28.000
receive high grades

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:31.000
in terms of uniqueness and relevance,

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:33.000
but low grades

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:35.000
in terms of knowledge and respect,

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:37.000
because they have existed on the market

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:39.000
not so long ago.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:41.000
The next method

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:43.000
is the so-called Morin method.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:45.000
Here we get

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:47.000
a more quantitative assessment.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:49.000
Here we can compare

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:50.000
the market capital of our brand

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:52.000
and the brand of competitors

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:54.000
not only on a regular scale,

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:56.000
that is, we can say not only

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:58.000
which brand has higher

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:00.000
or lower market capital,

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:02.000
but we can also compare

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:04.000
how much higher

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:06.000
and how much lower.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:08.000
You see the formula.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:10.000
The market capital is the sum of the market share

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:12.000
relative price and loyalty index.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:14.000
Relative price.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:16.000
What is it?

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:18.000
It is the percentage

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:20.000
of the price of our product,

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:22.000
the product of our brand,

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:24.000
higher than the price

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:26.000
of the product of the competitor's brand.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:28.000
And we see the following logic here.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:30.000
The higher the market share,

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:32.000
the higher the brand capital.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:34.000
And this is quite logical.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:36.000
If the product has a higher market share,

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:38.000
then, apparently,

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:40.000
this brand is attractive for buyers

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:42.000
and, perhaps, the brand capital

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:44.000
is really higher.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:46.000
The second aspect is the relative price.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:48.000
Here we see the following logic.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:50.000
Indeed,

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:52.000
if the price of our product,

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:54.000
the product of our brand,

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:56.000
is higher than the price of the competitor's product,

01:04:57.000 --> 01:04:58.000
and we really sell the product

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:00.000
at this price and still exist,

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:02.000
then, apparently,

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:04.000
there are some objective reasons

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:06.000
why buyers pay more for our product.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:08.000
Therefore, we have more market capital.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:10.000
And the next component of this formula

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:12.000
is the loyalty index.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:14.000
The loyalty index

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:16.000
is the percentage of buyers

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:18.000
who stated during the poll

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:20.000
that they plan to purchase our product,

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:22.000
to continue purchasing

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:24.000
our brand's product next year.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:26.000
Here we see the following logic.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:28.000
The more loyal buyers we have,

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:30.000
the higher the market capital.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:32.000
And now,

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:34.000
do the task from the workbook.

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:36.000
Compare the market capital

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:38.000
of your brand

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:40.000
and the brand of the competitor

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:42.000
you have chosen for analysis

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:44.000
and draw a conclusion

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:46.000
whose market capital is higher.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:50.000
The next step is to make a decision.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:52.000
The decision is made

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:54.000
based on the market capital

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:56.000
of the competitor.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:58.000
Now we move on

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:00.000
to the next group of marketing metrics

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:02.000
related to price management.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:04.000
The first indicator

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:06.000
that we need to consider

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:08.000
is the price premium.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:10.000
This is the ratio

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:12.000
of the difference between the price of our product

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.000
and the price of the competitor's product

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:16.000
to the price of the competitor's product.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:18.000
Knowing the price premium,

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:20.000
we can understand

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:22.000
how much our product is more expensive

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:24.000
than the competitor's product.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:26.000
Despite the price premium,

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:28.000
it can have a negative meaning.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:30.000
That is,

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:32.000
we need to measure the price premium

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:35.000
at all stages of product distribution.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:37.000
That is, at the level of the manufacturer's price,

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:39.000
at the level of the wholesale price

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:42.000
and at the level of the retail price.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:44.000
By calculating the price premium

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:46.000
of our products regularly,

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:48.000
we can see

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:50.000
the price premium of our products

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:52.000
relative to the competitors'.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:54.000
There are situations

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:56.000
when the price premium

01:06:57.000 --> 01:06:58.000
at the level of the manufacturer

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:00.000
has the same value

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:02.000
and at the level of the wholesale price

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:04.000
has a completely different value.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:06.000
Here we can see

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:08.000
how the power distribution changes.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:10.000
The next indicator

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:12.000
that we need to consider

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:14.000
is the so-called reserve price.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:16.000
What is a reserve price?

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:18.000
A reserve price is the price

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:20.000
at which our product is sold.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:22.000
You can see it

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:24.000
on the slide of the chart

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:26.000
where the reserve price is located.

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:28.000
There is also an indicator

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:30.000
of the maximum willingness to buy.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:32.000
This is the volume of sales

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:34.000
that we have

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:36.000
at a price equal to zero.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:38.000
Someone may say

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:40.000
that if the price of our product is zero,

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:42.000
then all our products will be taken away.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:44.000
This is not always the case.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:46.000
Here we can say

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:48.000
that if the price is zero,

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:50.000
then we will not sell our products,

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:52.000
because many buyers

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:54.000
will want to buy our products for free.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:56.000
But in fact,

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:58.000
the purchasing possibilities

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:00.000
have their own limitations.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:02.000
Therefore, the volume of sales

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:04.000
at a zero price is not infinite,

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:06.000
but has a certain level.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:08.000
Pay attention to the chart

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:10.000
where we can see

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:12.000
the maximum willingness to buy.

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:14.000
If we connect the points

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:16.000
of maximum willingness to buy

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:17.000
and the reserve price,

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:19.000
we will get

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:21.000
a linear demand function.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:23.000
Why do we study the reserve prices?

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:25.000
Knowing the reserve price,

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:27.000
the variable cost per unit of the product,

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:29.000
we can easily calculate

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:31.000
the optimal price of our product.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:33.000
It would seem

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:35.000
that this is not too simple.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:37.000
First, we need to make sure

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:39.000
that the optimal price

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:41.000
has a certain level of demand.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:43.000
If we calculate the optimal price

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:44.000
of our product,

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:46.000
we can calculate

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:48.000
the optimal price

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:50.000
that maximizes the profit of the company

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:52.000
according to this formula.

